<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2011/12/05/china-eac-in-investment-deal/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2011/12/05/china-eac-in-investment-deal/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The UN Economic Commission for Africa (UNECA) has called for a rationalisation and harmonisation of the treatment of sensitive products and tariff elimination commitments across EPAs with countries within the same regional economic community, as well as the establishment of coherence between rules of origin across EPAs and with rules of origin applied within regional economic arrangements. This probably poses the most substantive challenge within the COMESA region, given the different tariff elimination commitments and sensitive products contained in the various interim EPAs.</p><p>Agricultural trade and trade in value-added food products is likely to be at the heart of efforts to reconcile both differing sensitive produce designations and inconsistent rules of origin. Particular conflicts could arise around rules of origin issues between land-area-constrained economies such as those in the Indian Ocean, and land-rich regional economies that are actively trying to develop a range of agricultural sectors and associated value chains.</p><p>This would suggest a need for cross-representation of COMESA member state governments at the different negotiating sessions being held with COMESA member states in pursuit of comprehensive EPA arrangements. Given the trilateral FTA negotiations currently under way between COMESA, EAC and SADC, cross-representation may need to be extended still further in order to limit as far as possible contradictory commitments that could give rise to significant conflicts of interest within the Eastern and Southern African region (e.g. in the dairy, sugar, cereals and value-added cereal product sectors). This being noted, major tariff and non-tariff obstacles to the implementation of any T-FTA arrangement exist, suggesting that early implementation is unlikely.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
